{
  "texts": [
    "Similarly, we computed the cumulative power distribution CP ω by summing all the squared amplitude coefficients up to a certain threshold.",
    "For consistency, we measured the CP ω as a percentage score and chose the thresholds to be multiples of exact percentages i.e., ω 0 / 10%; 20%;.",
    "Both the power distribution P ω and cumulative power distribution CP ω can be used to compare dynamics between time series, but they have the inconvenience of not being scalar numbers.",
    "Furthermore, computing any distance-like metric (i.e., KL divergence) between these distributions across subjects would not yield any information of whether BOLD signals had slower dynamics (more power located in low frequencies) or the opposite (i.e., DMN in healthy and patient).",
    "To overcome this, we designed a DAS between time series based on the difference between two cumulative power distributions."
  ]
}